HEADWORD: Polysyndeton
<hw>Pol`y*syn"de*ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.,
from Gr. <grk>poly`s</grk> many + <?/ bound together, fr. <?/ to bind
together; <?/ with + <?/ to bind.]</ety> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>A
figure by which the conjunction is often repeated, as in the sentence,
⟦ldquo⟧We have ships and men and money and stores.⟦rdquo⟧ Opposed to
<contr>asyndeton</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

